{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_0_0182e95c", "content": "JSA has two specialized agent variants:\n\n**jsa-ci (CI/CD Security Agent)**\n- Focus: Application security in CI/CD pipelines\n- Handles: SAST, secrets detection, dependency scanning, code quality\n- Deployment: Runs as K8s pod watching GitHub webhooks and PR events\n- Workload: ~30% of security automation tasks\n\n**jsa-devsecops (DevSecOps Agent)**\n- Focus: Infrastructure and runtime security (GuidePoint specialty)\n- Handles: Kubernetes, Policy-as-Code, IaC, Cloud, Secrets Management, Compliance\n- Deployment: Runs as 24/7 K8s pod with domain schedulers\n- Workload: ~70% of security automation tasks\n\nBoth agents share:\n- Helm chart deployment pattern\n- CronJobs for log-sync and health-report\n- Slack notifications\n- State management via GP-Copilot API\n- Rank-based fix permissions (E/D/C/B/S)", "token_count": 197, "char_count": 794, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 0, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.238021", "content_hash": "0182e95c3943c9a5"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_1_1424ab60", "content": "jsa-ci uses these scanners in src/scanners/:\n\n**Secrets Detection:**\n- gitleaks_scan_npc.py - Detects hardcoded secrets, API keys, tokens\n\n**SAST (Static Analysis):**\n- bandit_scan_npc.py - Python security analysis (SQL injection, XSS, command injection)\n- semgrep_scan_npc.py - Multi-language SAST with custom rules\n- eslint_scan_npc.py - JavaScript/TypeScript security linting\n\n**Code Quality:**\n- hadolint_scan_npc.py - Dockerfile best practices\n\n**CI/CD Security:**\n- gha_scanner_npc.py - GitHub Actions security (unpinned actions, injection risks)\n- github_api_npc.py - GitHub API integration for PR comments, status checks\n\nAll scanners follow the BaseNPC pattern with standardized run() method returning normalized findings.", "token_count": 169, "char_count": 731, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 1, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.238365", "content_hash": "1424ab608f9453f5"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_2_19ff5c3b", "content": "jsa-devsecops uses these scanners in src/scanners/:\n\n**Kubernetes Security:**\n- kubescape_scan_npc.py - K8s security posture (NSA, MITRE frameworks)\n- polaris_scan_npc.py - K8s best practices and workload validation\n- kubebench_scan_npc.py - CIS Kubernetes benchmarks\n- kubectl_diagnostics_npc.py - Runtime K8s diagnostics\n\n**Infrastructure as Code:**\n- checkov_scan_npc.py - Terraform, CloudFormation, Helm scanning\n- tfsec_scan_npc.py - Terraform-specific security\n- conftest_scan_npc.py - OPA/Rego policy testing\n\n**Vulnerability Scanning:**\n- trivy_scan_npc.py - Container images, filesystems, IaC, SBOM\n- grype_scan_npc.py - SCA vulnerability scanning\n- snyk_scan_npc.py - Commercial SCA integration\n\n**Cloud Security:**\n- prowler_scan_npc.py - AWS security auditing\n- infrastructure_scanner_npc.py - Multi-cloud infrastructure scanning", "token_count": 214, "char_count": 841, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 2, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.238749", "content_hash": "19ff5c3bae378136"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_3_07fea548", "content": "jsa-ci fixers are in src/fixers/ and handle application-level remediation:\n\n**Secrets Fixes (D-rank, auto-fix):**\n- Remove hardcoded secrets from code\n- Add patterns to .gitignore\n- Rotate exposed credentials via API\n\n**Dependency Fixes (D-rank, auto-fix):**\n- yarn upgrade / npm update for JS vulnerabilities\n- pip-compile / poetry update for Python\n- Generate lock files with fixed versions\n\n**Code Fixes (C-rank, approval required):**\n- SQL injection: Parameterized queries\n- XSS: Output encoding\n- Command injection: Input sanitization\n- Path traversal: Path validation\n\n**CI/CD Fixes (D-rank, auto-fix):**\n- Pin GitHub Actions to SHA\n- Fix workflow injection vulnerabilities\n- Add security scanning steps to pipelines\n\nFix orchestration via fix_orchestrator.py which coordinates multiple fixers per finding.", "token_count": 188, "char_count": 812, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 3, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.239124", "content_hash": "07fea5487e295c75"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_4_1d5ed833", "content": "jsa-devsecops fixers are organized by domain in src/fixers/:\n\n**Kubernetes Fixes (k8s_*):**\n- k8s_pod_patcher_npc.py - Add security contexts, resource limits\n- k8s_network_policy_generator_npc.py - Generate NetworkPolicies\n- k8s_deployment_updater_npc.py - Fix deployment misconfigs\n- k8s_kubernetes_fixer_npc.py - General K8s remediation\n- k8s_rbac_scoper.py - Scope down overly permissive RBAC\n- k8s_probe_adder.py - Add liveness/readiness probes\n- k8s_resource_limits.py - Add CPU/memory limits\n- k8s_security_context.py - Add runAsNonRoot, drop capabilities\n- k8s_pod_security_enforcer.py - Enforce Pod Security Standards\n\n**Policy Fixes (policy_*):**\n- policy_rego_generator.py - Generate OPA/Rego policies\n- policy_constraint_creator.py - Create Gatekeeper constraints\n- policy_kyverno_creator.py - Generate Kyverno policies\n- policy_mutation_creator.py - Create policy mutations\n- policy_exception_manager.py - Handle policy exceptions\n\n**IaC Fixes (iac_*):**\n- iac_terraform_fixer.py - Fix Terraform misconfigs\n- iac_helm_fixer.py - Fix Helm chart issues\n- iac_conftest_fixer_npc.py - Fix OPA policy violations\n- iac_cloudformation_fixer.py - Fix CloudFormation templates\n- iac_drift_reconciler.py - Reconcile infrastructure drift\n\n**Cloud Fixes (cloud_*):**\n- cloud_iam_fixer.py - Fix IAM policy issues\n- cloud_s3_fixer.py - Fix S3 bucket configs\n- cloud_ec2_fixer.py - Fix EC2 security groups\n- cloud_vpc_fixer.py - Fix VPC configurations\n\n**Secrets Fixes (secrets_*):**\n- secrets_secret_rotator.py - Rotate secrets\n- secrets_sealed_secret_converter.py - Convert to SealedSecrets\n- secrets_secret_migrator.py - Migrate secrets to Vault", "token_count": 441, "char_count": 1645, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 4, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.239729", "content_hash": "1d5ed8338b6309e5"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_5_b521aeb9", "content": "Both JSA agents deploy via Helm charts in GP-BEDROCK-AGENTS/charts/:\n\n**jsa-ci Deployment:**\n```bash\nhelm upgrade --install jsa-ci ./charts/jsa-ci \\\n  --namespace portfolio \\\n  --set gpcopilot.instance=02-instance \\\n  --set gpcopilot.slot=slot-3\n```\n\n**jsa-devsecops Deployment:**\n```bash\nhelm upgrade --install jsa-devsecops ./charts/jsa-devsecops \\\n  --namespace portfolio \\\n  --set gpcopilot.instance=02-instance \\\n  --set gpcopilot.slot=slot-3\n```\n\n**Key Helm Values:**\n- agent.rank: C (determines RBAC and auto-fix permissions)\n- agent.autoFix: true/false\n- agent.dryRun: true for testing\n- gpcopilot.endpoint: GP-GUI API URL\n- gpcopilot.instance/slot: Target project location\n- domains.*: Enable/disable security domains\n- notifications.slack.webhookUrlSecret: Slack integration\n\n**Resources Created:**\n- Deployment (main agent pod)\n- ServiceAccount with RBAC\n- CronJobs (log-sync, health-report, cve-tracker)\n- ConfigMap for agent config\n- NetworkPolicy for traffic control\n- ServiceMonitor for Prometheus", "token_count": 277, "char_count": 1012, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 5, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.240149", "content_hash": "b521aeb9f613ea44"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_6_578dc892", "content": "JSA agents run these CronJobs for automation:\n\n**jsa-ci CronJobs:**\n1. **jsa-ci-log-sync** (*/15 * * * *)\n   - Syncs operational logs to CloudWatch/S3\n   - Feeds RAG pipeline for JADE training\n   - Script: /app/scripts/log_sync.py\n\n2. **jsa-ci-health-report** (0 8 * * *)\n   - Daily Slack summary at 8am UTC\n   - Reports: scans run, findings, fix rate, escalations\n   - Script: /app/scripts/health_report.py\n\n**jsa-devsecops CronJobs:**\n1. **jsa-devsecops-log-sync** (*/15 * * * *)\n   - Same as jsa-ci, syncs to RAG pipeline\n\n2. **jsa-devsecops-health-report** (0 8 * * *)\n   - Daily Slack summary for DevSecOps domains\n\n3. **jsa-devsecops-cve-tracker** (0 6 * * *)\n   - Daily CVE scan at 6am UTC (before health report)\n   - Scans production container images with Trivy\n   - Reports HIGH/CRITICAL vulnerabilities to Slack\n   - Script: /app/scripts/cve_tracker.py\n\n**Pipeline Flow:**\n6am: CVE scan images -> 8am: Health summary -> Every 15min: Logs to RAG", "token_count": 292, "char_count": 954, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 6, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.240498", "content_hash": "578dc8925e9de17b"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_7_7c249bcf", "content": "jsa-devsecops uses a priority-based domain scheduler (src/scheduler.py):\n\n**Priority Levels:**\n- CRITICAL (1 min interval): kubernetes, policy\n- HIGH (5 min interval): iac, cloud-aws, cloud-azure, cloud-gcp\n- MEDIUM (15 min interval): secrets, compliance\n\n**Scheduler Logic:**\n```python\nclass DomainScheduler:\n    DOMAIN_PRIORITIES = {\n        'kubernetes': 'CRITICAL',  # GuidePoint specialty\n        'policy': 'CRITICAL',      # OPA/Gatekeeper/Kyverno\n        'iac': 'HIGH',\n        'cloud-aws': 'HIGH',\n        'secrets': 'MEDIUM',\n        'compliance': 'MEDIUM'\n    }\n```\n\n**Scheduling Flow:**\n1. Agent loop calls scheduler.domains_to_scan()\n2. Returns list of domains past their scan interval\n3. Agent runs analyzers for each domain\n4. scheduler.mark_scanned(domain) updates timestamp\n5. scheduler.next_scan_time() determines sleep duration\n\nThis ensures Kubernetes and Policy issues are caught within 1 minute while less critical domains are checked periodically.", "token_count": 240, "char_count": 969, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 7, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.240892", "content_hash": "7c249bcf361f38e4"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_8_cee8110c", "content": "jsa-devsecops analyzers are in src/analyzers/ with domain prefixes:\n\n**Kubernetes (k8s_*):**\n- k8s_kubernetes_analyzer.py - Main K8s security analyzer\n- k8s_pod_analyzer.py - Pod security analysis\n- k8s_deployment_analyzer.py - Deployment misconfigs\n- k8s_service_analyzer.py - Service exposure risks\n- k8s_node_analyzer.py - Node security posture\n- k8s_networkpolicy.py - NetworkPolicy coverage\n- k8s_rbac.py - RBAC over-permissions\n- k8s_secrets.py - K8s secrets exposure\n- k8s_pod_security.py - PSS/PSP compliance\n- k8s_probes.py - Missing health probes\n- k8s_resources.py - Missing resource limits\n- k8s_images.py - Image security (tags, registries)\n\n**Policy (policy_*):**\n- policy_rego_analyzer.py - OPA/Rego policy analysis\n- policy_constraint_analyzer.py - Gatekeeper constraints\n- policy_coverage_analyzer.py - Policy coverage gaps\n- policy_conflict_detector.py - Policy conflicts\n\n**Cloud (cloud_*):**\n- cloud_iam_analyzer.py - IAM policy analysis\n- cloud_s3_analyzer.py - S3 bucket security\n- cloud_ec2_analyzer.py - EC2 security groups\n- cloud_vpc_analyzer.py - VPC configurations\n- cloud_guardduty_analyzer.py - GuardDuty findings\n- cloud_securityhub_analyzer.py - Security Hub integration\n\n**IaC (iac_*):**\n- iac_terraform_analyzer.py - Terraform analysis\n- iac_helm_analyzer.py - Helm chart analysis\n- iac_cloudformation_analyzer.py - CFN analysis\n- iac_drift_detector.py - Infrastructure drift\n- iac_compliance_checker.py - IaC compliance\n\n**Secrets (secrets_*):**\n- secrets_rotation_analyzer.py - Rotation compliance\n- secrets_exposure_analyzer.py - Exposure detection\n- secrets_encryption_analyzer.py - Encryption at rest\n\n**Compliance (compliance_*):**\n- compliance_gap_analyzer.py - Framework gap analysis\n- compliance_control_mapper.py - Control mapping\n- compliance_evidence_collector.py - Audit evidence", "token_count": 481, "char_count": 1826, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 8, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.241458", "content_hash": "cee8110c00a60039"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_9_10c532db", "content": "jsa-devsecops watchers are in src/watchers/ for real-time monitoring:\n\n**Kubernetes (k8s_*):**\n- k8s_events.py - Watch K8s events for security issues\n- k8s_admission.py - Admission webhook events\n- k8s_audit.py - Audit log monitoring\n- k8s_drift.py - Configuration drift detection\n- k8s_log_watcher.py - Pod log analysis\n\n**Policy (policy_*):**\n- policy_gatekeeper.py - Gatekeeper constraint violations\n- policy_kyverno.py - Kyverno policy reports\n- policy_conftest.py - Conftest policy changes\n\n**Cloud (cloud_*):**\n- cloud_iam_watcher.py - IAM changes\n- cloud_s3_watcher.py - S3 bucket changes\n- cloud_ec2_watcher.py - EC2/SG changes\n- cloud_vpc_watcher.py - VPC modifications\n\n**IaC (iac_*):**\n- iac_terraform_watcher.py - Terraform state changes\n- iac_helm_watcher.py - Helm release changes\n- iac_cloudformation_watcher.py - CFN stack events\n\n**Secrets (secrets_*):**\n- secrets_vault_watcher.py - Vault secret access\n- secrets_k8s_secrets_watcher.py - K8s secret changes\n- secrets_aws_secrets_watcher.py - AWS Secrets Manager\n\nWatchers run in the main agent loop and trigger immediate analysis when events occur.", "token_count": 311, "char_count": 1116, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 9, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.241816", "content_hash": "10c532db96dda069"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_10_12032b36", "content": "jsa-devsecops includes compliance templates in src/templates/:\n\n**Policy Templates (policy_*):**\n- policy_pss.py - Pod Security Standards (baseline, restricted)\n- policy_cis.py - CIS Kubernetes Benchmarks\n- policy_nist.py - NIST 800-53 controls\n- policy_soc2.py - SOC2 security controls\n- policy_pci.py - PCI-DSS requirements\n\n**Compliance Frameworks (compliance_*):**\n- compliance_cis.py - CIS benchmark mappings\n- compliance_nist.py - NIST 800-53 Rev5\n- compliance_soc2.py - SOC2 Type II\n- compliance_pci.py - PCI-DSS v4.0\n- compliance_hipaa.py - HIPAA Security Rule\n- compliance_fedramp.py - FedRAMP controls\n\n**Usage:**\nTemplates provide:\n- Control definitions and requirements\n- Mapping to scanner findings\n- Remediation guidance\n- Evidence collection requirements\n- Gap analysis reports\n\nThe compliance_mapper_npc.py uses these templates to generate compliance reports from scan findings.", "token_count": 216, "char_count": 894, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 10, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.242124", "content_hash": "12032b36196914c2"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_11_eda6b778", "content": "jsa-ci and jsa-devsecops coordinate through GP-Copilot state management:\n\n**Division of Responsibility:**\n- jsa-ci: Code-level issues (runs on PR/commit events)\n- jsa-devsecops: Infrastructure issues (runs 24/7 on schedule)\n\n**State Sharing via GP-Copilot:**\n```\nGP-PROJECTS/{instance}/{slot}/jsa/\n��������� scans/       # Both agents write scan results\n��������� fixes/       # Both agents log fix attempts\n��������� escalations/ # Shared escalation queue\n��������� state.json   # Shared agent state\n```\n\n**Handoff Scenarios:**\n1. jsa-ci finds Dockerfile issue -> escalates to jsa-devsecops for K8s impact\n2. jsa-devsecops finds dependency CVE -> jsa-ci handles package upgrade\n3. Both detect same secret -> jsa-ci removes from code, jsa-devsecops rotates in Vault\n\n**Coordination Rules:**\n- Same finding = first agent claims ownership\n- Cross-domain = escalate to appropriate agent\n- B/S rank = both escalate to human\n\n**Log Sync Pipeline:**\nBoth agents sync logs every 15min -> GP-OPENSEARCH RAG -> JADE learns patterns", "token_count": 265, "char_count": 1022, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 11, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.242563", "content_hash": "eda6b7782dcc9fe8"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_12_dbf6bee1", "content": "jsa-devsecops/src/ uses a flat structure with domain prefixes:\n\n```\nsrc/\n��������� main.py              # Entry point, CLI parsing\n��������� agent.py             # Main agent loop (DevSecOpsAgent)\n��������� config.py            # AgentConfig from environment\n��������� scheduler.py         # Domain priority scheduler\n���\n��������� scanners/            # External tool wrappers (12 NPCs)\n���   ��������� trivy_scan_npc.py\n���   ��������� kubescape_scan_npc.py\n���   ��������� checkov_scan_npc.py\n���   ��������� ...\n���\n��������� analyzers/           # Finding analyzers (47 files)\n���   ��������� k8s_*.py         # Kubernetes analyzers\n���   ��������� policy_*.py      # Policy analyzers\n���   ��������� cloud_*.py       # Cloud analyzers\n���   ��������� iac_*.py         # IaC analyzers\n���   ��������� secrets_*.py     # Secrets analyzers\n���   ��������� compliance_*.py  # Compliance analyzers\n���\n��������� fixers/              # Remediation fixers (33 files)\n���   ��������� k8s_*.py         # Kubernetes fixers\n���   ��������� policy_*.py      # Policy fixers\n���   ��������� cloud_*.py       # Cloud fixers\n���   ��������� iac_*.py         # IaC fixers\n���   ��������� secrets_*.py     # Secrets fixers\n���\n��������� watchers/            # Real-time monitors (18 files)\n���   ��������� k8s_*.py         # K8s event watchers\n���   ��������� policy_*.py      # Policy watchers\n���   ��������� cloud_*.py       # Cloud watchers\n���   ��������� iac_*.py         # IaC watchers\n���   ��������� secrets_*.py     # Secrets watchers\n���\n��������� templates/           # Compliance templates (11 files)\n    ��������� policy_*.py      # Policy templates\n    ��������� compliance_*.py  # Framework templates\n```\n\nThis flat structure with prefixes matches jsa-ci's organization for consistency.", "token_count": 488, "char_count": 1791, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 12, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.243731", "content_hash": "dbf6bee1608c1def"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_13_1c1401e5", "content": "jsa-ci/src/ structure:\n\n```\nsrc/\n��������� __init__.py\n��������� main.py              # Entry point\n��������� agent.py             # CISecurityAgent main loop\n��������� base_npc.py          # BaseNPC abstract class\n��������� jade_client.py       # JADE model client\n��������� fix_orchestrator.py  # Multi-fixer coordination\n���\n��������� config/              # Configuration\n���   ��������� agent_config.py\n���\n��������� scanners/            # Scanner NPCs (7 tools)\n���   ��������� gitleaks_scan_npc.py\n���   ��������� bandit_scan_npc.py\n���   ��������� semgrep_scan_npc.py\n���   ��������� eslint_scan_npc.py\n���   ��������� hadolint_scan_npc.py\n���   ��������� gha_scanner_npc.py\n���   ��������� github_api_npc.py\n���\n��������� fixers/              # Fixer NPCs\n���   ��������� secrets_fixer_npc.py\n���   ��������� dependency_fixer_npc.py\n���   ��������� code_fixer_npc.py\n���   ��������� ci_fixer_npc.py\n���\n��������� analyzers/           # Finding analyzers\n���   ��������� severity_analyzer.py\n���   ��������� rank_classifier.py\n���\n��������� watchers/            # Event watchers\n���   ��������� github_webhook_watcher.py\n���   ��������� pr_watcher.py\n���\n��������� knowledge/           # Knowledge base\n    ��������� vulnerability_patterns.py\n```\n\njsa-ci focuses on CI/CD pipeline security with fewer, more specialized NPCs.", "token_count": 361, "char_count": 1331, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 13, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.244530", "content_hash": "1c1401e587d59d22"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_14_1f411173", "content": "The CVE tracker (jsa-devsecops/scripts/cve_tracker.py) scans container images daily:\n\n**Schedule:** 0 6 * * * (6am UTC, before health report)\n\n**Flow:**\n1. Load image list from CVE_IMAGES env or defaults\n2. For each image, run: trivy image --severity HIGH,CRITICAL --format json\n3. Extract vulnerabilities from Trivy JSON output\n4. Generate summary report with counts\n5. Save JSON report to /data/state/cve-reports/\n6. Send Slack notification if webhook configured\n\n**Configuration (values.yaml):**\n```yaml\ncronjobs:\n  cveTracker:\n    enabled: true\n    schedule: \"0 6 * * *\"\n    severity: \"HIGH,CRITICAL\"\n    slack: true\n    images: \"app:v1,api:v2\"  # Optional override\n```\n\n**Slack Message Format:**\n- Header with status emoji (rotating_light/warning/check)\n- Per-image summary (CRITICAL/HIGH counts)\n- Top 5 CVEs across all images\n- Links to remediation\n\n**Exit Codes:**\n- 0: No HIGH/CRITICAL CVEs\n- 1: HIGH CVEs found\n- 2: CRITICAL CVEs found\n\nUsed by K8s Job to determine success/failure for alerting.", "token_count": 282, "char_count": 1005, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 14, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.245025", "content_hash": "1f411173031bcf8e"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_15_4bbcc8f8", "content": "JSA agents need RBAC permissions based on their rank and domains:\n\n**jsa-ci RBAC (CI/CD focused):**\n```yaml\n- apiGroups: [\"\"]  # Read pods, configmaps, secrets\n  resources: [\"pods\", \"configmaps\", \"secrets\"]\n  verbs: [\"get\", \"list\", \"watch\"]\n- apiGroups: [\"apps\"]\n  resources: [\"deployments\"]\n  verbs: [\"get\", \"list\", \"watch\", \"patch\"]  # For image updates\n```\n\n**jsa-devsecops RBAC (full K8s security):**\n```yaml\n# Core resources\n- apiGroups: [\"\", \"apps\", \"batch\"]\n  resources: [\"*\"]\n  verbs: [\"get\", \"list\", \"watch\"]\n\n# Write permissions for fixes (C-rank)\n- apiGroups: [\"\"]\n  resources: [\"pods\", \"services\", \"configmaps\", \"networkpolicies\"]\n  verbs: [\"patch\", \"update\"]\n\n# Policy resources\n- apiGroups: [\"constraints.gatekeeper.sh\", \"kyverno.io\"]\n  resources: [\"*\"]\n  verbs: [\"get\", \"list\", \"watch\", \"create\", \"patch\"]\n\n# RBAC analysis\n- apiGroups: [\"rbac.authorization.k8s.io\"]\n  resources: [\"roles\", \"rolebindings\", \"clusterroles\"]\n  verbs: [\"get\", \"list\", \"watch\"]\n```\n\n**Rank-Based Permissions:**\n- E-rank: Read-only (get, list, watch)\n- D-rank: Limited write (patch safe resources)\n- C-rank: Standard write (most resources, with approval)\n- B-rank: Elevated (RBAC, policies, requires escalation)\n- S-rank: Admin (cluster-wide, human required)", "token_count": 373, "char_count": 1249, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 15, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.245550", "content_hash": "4bbcc8f8b51ddc6b"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_16_bf183db3", "content": "Deploy both JSA agents to the portfolio namespace:\n\n**1. Create namespace and secrets:**\n```bash\nkubectl create namespace portfolio\n\n# Slack webhook secret\nkubectl create secret generic slack-webhook \\\n  --namespace portfolio \\\n  --from-literal=webhook-url='https://hooks.slack.com/...'\n\n# GP-Copilot API key (if needed)\nkubectl create secret generic gpcopilot-api-key \\\n  --namespace portfolio \\\n  --from-literal=api-key='your-api-key'\n```\n\n**2. Deploy jsa-ci:**\n```bash\nhelm upgrade --install jsa-ci \\\n  ./GP-BEDROCK-AGENTS/charts/jsa-ci \\\n  --namespace portfolio \\\n  --set gpcopilot.instance=02-instance \\\n  --set gpcopilot.slot=slot-3 \\\n  --set notifications.slack.webhookUrlSecret.enabled=true\n```\n\n**3. Deploy jsa-devsecops:**\n```bash\nhelm upgrade --install jsa-devsecops \\\n  ./GP-BEDROCK-AGENTS/charts/jsa-devsecops \\\n  --namespace portfolio \\\n  --set gpcopilot.instance=02-instance \\\n  --set gpcopilot.slot=slot-3 \\\n  --set notifications.slack.webhookUrlSecret.enabled=true \\\n  --set cronjobs.cveTracker.images='myapp:v1\\,myapi:v2'\n```\n\n**4. Verify deployment:**\n```bash\nkubectl get pods -n portfolio\nkubectl get cronjobs -n portfolio\nkubectl logs -n portfolio deploy/jsa-ci\nkubectl logs -n portfolio deploy/jsa-devsecops\n```\n\n**5. Check CronJobs:**\n```bash\nkubectl get cronjobs -n portfolio\n# jsa-ci-log-sync, jsa-ci-health-report\n# jsa-devsecops-log-sync, jsa-devsecops-health-report, jsa-devsecops-cve-tracker\n```", "token_count": 404, "char_count": 1424, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 16, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.246096", "content_hash": "bf183db3dcc76baa"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_17_4286a780", "content": "jsa-devsecops domains are configured in values.yaml:\n\n**Kubernetes Domain:**\n```yaml\ndomains:\n  kubernetes:\n    enabled: true\n    namespaces: [\"*\"]  # or [\"prod\", \"staging\"]\n    excludeNamespaces: [\"kube-system\", \"kube-public\"]\n```\n\n**Policy-as-Code Domain:**\n```yaml\n  policy:\n    enabled: true\n    frameworks:\n      opa: true\n      gatekeeper: true\n      kyverno: true\n      conftest: true\n```\n\n**Infrastructure-as-Code Domain:**\n```yaml\n  iac:\n    enabled: true\n    providers:\n      terraform: true\n      cloudformation: false\n      arm: false\n```\n\n**Cloud Security Domain:**\n```yaml\n  cloud:\n    enabled: true\n    providers:\n      aws:\n        enabled: true\n        credentialsSecret:\n          enabled: false\n          name: \"aws-credentials\"\n      azure:\n        enabled: false\n      gcp:\n        enabled: false\n```\n\n**Secrets Management Domain:**\n```yaml\n  secrets:\n    enabled: true\n    providers:\n      vault: false\n      awsSecretsManager: true\n      k8sSecrets: true\n```\n\n**Compliance Domain:**\n```yaml\n  compliance:\n    enabled: true\n    frameworks:\n      cis: true\n      nist: true\n      soc2: true\n      pci: false\n      hipaa: false\n      fedramp: false\n```\n\nDisabled domains skip their schedulers, analyzers, and fixers entirely.", "token_count": 336, "char_count": 1245, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 17, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.246750", "content_hash": "4286a78069fd72c9"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_18_1f2bd6f3", "content": "JSA uses a rank system to determine automation level for findings:\n\n**E-Rank (95-100% confidence, auto-fix):**\n- Hardcoded secrets in code\n- Missing .gitignore entries\n- Unpinned GitHub Actions\n- Missing resource limits (obvious patterns)\n\n**D-Rank (70-90% confidence, auto-fix with logging):**\n- SQL injection (clear patterns)\n- XSS vulnerabilities\n- Dependency CVEs with known fixes\n- Basic K8s misconfigs (no securityContext)\n\n**C-Rank (40-70% confidence, requires approval):**\n- Complex multi-file fixes\n- NetworkPolicy generation\n- RBAC scope reduction\n- Terraform/IaC modifications\n- Policy creation (Gatekeeper, Kyverno)\n\n**B-Rank (20-40% confidence, escalate to human):**\n- Architecture changes\n- Cross-service modifications\n- Compliance gaps requiring business decisions\n- Performance vs security tradeoffs\n\n**S-Rank (0-5% confidence, human required):**\n- Org-wide policy decisions\n- Incident response\n- Zero-trust architecture design\n- Compliance attestations\n\n**Agent Behavior by Rank:**\n- E/D: Auto-fix immediately, log result\n- C: Send to Slack for approval, wait for response\n- B/S: Create escalation ticket, notify humans\n\nRank is determined by the agent's brain (JADE model) analyzing finding context.", "token_count": 292, "char_count": 1217, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 18, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.247470", "content_hash": "1f2bd6f3b1ae8510"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_19_a63c727a", "content": "JSA agents expose Prometheus metrics on port 9100:\n\n**Common Metrics (both agents):**\n```\n# Scan metrics\njsa_scans_total{scanner=\"trivy\", status=\"success\"}\njsa_scan_duration_seconds{scanner=\"gitleaks\"}\njsa_findings_total{severity=\"CRITICAL\", domain=\"kubernetes\"}\n\n# Fix metrics\njsa_fixes_attempted_total{rank=\"D\", domain=\"secrets\"}\njsa_fixes_succeeded_total{rank=\"C\"}\njsa_fix_duration_seconds{fixer=\"dependency_fixer\"}\n\n# Escalation metrics\njsa_escalations_total{rank=\"B\", reason=\"architecture_change\"}\njsa_approval_wait_seconds{rank=\"C\"}\n\n# Agent health\njsa_agent_up{agent=\"jsa-devsecops\"}\njsa_last_scan_timestamp{domain=\"kubernetes\"}\njsa_queue_depth{type=\"pending_fixes\"}\n```\n\n**jsa-devsecops Specific:**\n```\njsa_domain_scan_interval_seconds{domain=\"policy\"}\njsa_watcher_events_total{watcher=\"k8s_events\"}\njsa_policy_violations_total{framework=\"gatekeeper\"}\n```\n\n**ServiceMonitor (for Prometheus Operator):**\n```yaml\nmetrics:\n  enabled: true\n  port: 9100\n  serviceMonitor:\n    enabled: true\n    interval: 30s\n    labels:\n      release: prometheus\n```\n\nMetrics feed Grafana dashboards for security posture visualization.", "token_count": 304, "char_count": 1121, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 19, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.247987", "content_hash": "a63c727ac693d33c"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_20_071ec989", "content": "log_sync.py (in both agents' scripts/) syncs operational logs to RAG:\n\n**Schedule:** */15 * * * * (every 15 minutes)\n\n**Flow:**\n1. Read logs from /data/state/ (scans, fixes, escalations)\n2. Format as JSONL for RAG ingestion\n3. Upload to GP-OPENSEARCH/01-unprocessed/operational-logs/\n4. Optionally push to CloudWatch/S3\n\n**Log Types Synced:**\n```\n/data/state/\n��������� scans/          # Scan result JSONs\n��������� fixes/          # Fix attempt logs\n��������� escalations/    # Escalation records\n��������� cycles/         # Full cycle reports\n```\n\n**JSONL Format:**\n```json\n{\"timestamp\": \"2026-01-02T...\", \"agent\": \"jsa-ci\", \"type\": \"scan\", \"scanner\": \"gitleaks\", \"findings\": 3}\n{\"timestamp\": \"2026-01-02T...\", \"agent\": \"jsa-devsecops\", \"type\": \"fix\", \"domain\": \"kubernetes\", \"success\": true}\n```\n\n**RAG Pipeline:**\n```\nlog_sync.py -> GP-OPENSEARCH/01-unprocessed/\n            -> GP-OPENSEARCH/02-preparation-factory/\n            -> GP-OPENSEARCH/03-preprocessed/\n            -> GP-OPENSEARCH/04-ingesting/\n            -> ChromaDB (JADE RAG)\n```\n\nJADE learns from operational patterns to improve future decisions.", "token_count": 332, "char_count": 1115, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 20, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.248451", "content_hash": "071ec9896761f2de"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_21_1567fc40", "content": "JSA agents support multiple notification channels:\n\n**Slack Notifications:**\n```yaml\nnotifications:\n  slack:\n    enabled: true\n    webhookUrlSecret:\n      enabled: true\n      name: \"slack-webhook\"\n      key: \"webhook-url\"\n    channel: \"#security-alerts\"\n    severities: [CRITICAL, HIGH]\n```\n\n**Notification Types:**\n1. **Finding Alerts** - New CRITICAL/HIGH findings\n2. **C-Rank Approvals** - Interactive approve/deny buttons\n3. **Fix Results** - Success/failure notifications\n4. **Health Reports** - Daily summary (8am)\n5. **CVE Reports** - Daily image scan (6am)\n6. **Escalations** - B/S rank findings requiring human review\n\n**Email Notifications:**\n```yaml\n  email:\n    enabled: true\n    smtpHost: \"smtp.example.com\"\n    from: \"jsa@linkops.ai\"\n    to: [\"security-team@linkops.ai\"]\n```\n\n**PagerDuty Integration:**\n```yaml\n  pagerduty:\n    enabled: true\n    integrationKeySecret:\n      enabled: true\n      name: \"pagerduty-key\"\n    severities: [CRITICAL]  # Only page for critical\n```\n\n**Slack Message Examples:**\n- :rotating_light: CRITICAL: SQL Injection in api/users.py [Approve] [Deny]\n- :white_check_mark: Fixed 3 dependency CVEs in package.json\n- :warning: Daily Health: 5 scans, 12 findings, 80% fix rate", "token_count": 334, "char_count": 1213, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 21, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.248934", "content_hash": "1567fc40e84626f8"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_22_b657b368", "content": "health_report.py generates daily Slack summaries for both agents:\n\n**Schedule:** 0 8 * * * (8am UTC daily)\n\n**Flow:**\n1. Parse logs from last 24 hours in /data/state/\n2. Count scans, findings by severity, fixes attempted/succeeded\n3. Calculate fix rate percentage\n4. Format Slack blocks message\n5. Send to SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\n\n**Summary Data Collected:**\n```python\nsummary = {\n    'total_scans': 0,\n    'total_findings': 0,\n    'by_severity': {'CRITICAL': 0, 'HIGH': 0, 'MEDIUM': 0, 'LOW': 0},\n    'by_rank': {'E': 0, 'D': 0, 'C': 0, 'B': 0, 'S': 0},\n    'fixes_attempted': 0,\n    'fixes_succeeded': 0,\n    'escalations': 0,\n    'errors': []\n}\n```\n\n**Health Status Logic:**\n- :rotating_light: Critical Findings - CRITICAL > 0\n- :warning: Degraded - errors present\n- :large_blue_circle: Operational - findings but no critical\n- :white_check_mark: Healthy - no findings\n\n**Slack Message Sections:**\n- Header with status emoji\n- Status and report time\n- Last 24 hours summary\n- Scan count, finding count\n- Critical/High counts\n- Fix rate percentage\n- Rank distribution\n- Error list (if any)", "token_count": 329, "char_count": 1085, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 22, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.249504", "content_hash": "b657b368dba16211"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_23_fffd59a8", "content": "Both JSA agents run an async main loop in agent.py:\n\n**jsa-ci (CISecurityAgent):**\n```python\nasync def run(self):\n    while True:\n        # 1. Check for GitHub webhook events\n        events = await self.watcher.get_pending_events()\n        \n        for event in events:\n            # 2. Run relevant scanners\n            findings = await self.scan(event.target)\n            \n            # 3. Classify findings by rank\n            ranked = self.rank_classifier.classify(findings)\n            \n            # 4. Auto-fix E/D rank\n            for finding in ranked['E'] + ranked['D']:\n                await self.fix_orchestrator.fix(finding)\n            \n            # 5. Send C-rank for approval\n            for finding in ranked['C']:\n                await self.slack.request_approval(finding)\n            \n            # 6. Escalate B/S rank\n            for finding in ranked['B'] + ranked['S']:\n                await self.escalate(finding)\n        \n        await asyncio.sleep(10)  # Poll interval\n```\n\n**jsa-devsecops (DevSecOpsAgent):**\n```python\nasync def run(self):\n    while True:\n        # 1. Get domains ready to scan\n        domains = self.scheduler.domains_to_scan()\n        \n        for domain in domains:\n            # 2. Run domain analyzers\n            findings = await self.analyze_domain(domain)\n            \n            # 3. Process findings by rank\n            await self.process_findings(findings)\n            \n            # 4. Mark domain scanned\n            self.scheduler.mark_scanned(domain)\n        \n        # 5. Check watchers for real-time events\n        await self.check_watchers()\n        \n        # 6. Sleep until next domain ready\n        sleep_time = self.scheduler.next_scan_time()\n        await asyncio.sleep(min(sleep_time, 60))\n```\n\nBoth agents emit Prometheus metrics throughout the loop.", "token_count": 400, "char_count": 1822, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 23, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.250203", "content_hash": "fffd59a88de49568"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_24_b3f3945f", "content": "Both JSA Helm charts have these templates in charts/{agent}/templates/:\n\n**Common Templates:**\n- deployment.yaml - Main agent pod\n- service.yaml - ClusterIP for metrics\n- serviceaccount.yaml - K8s ServiceAccount\n- configmap.yaml - Agent configuration\n- secret.yaml - Sensitive config (if not using external)\n- rbac.yaml - ClusterRole and ClusterRoleBinding\n- networkpolicy.yaml - Pod traffic control\n- servicemonitor.yaml - Prometheus scraping\n- _helpers.tpl - Template helper functions\n\n**jsa-ci Specific:**\n- cronjob-log-sync.yaml - Log sync every 15min\n- cronjob-health-report.yaml - Daily 8am report\n\n**jsa-devsecops Specific:**\n- cronjob-log-sync.yaml - Log sync every 15min\n- cronjob-health-report.yaml - Daily 8am report\n- cronjob-cve-tracker.yaml - Daily 6am CVE scan\n\n**Chart Structure:**\n```\ncharts/jsa-{agent}/\n��������� Chart.yaml           # Chart metadata\n��������� values.yaml          # Default values\n��������� templates/\n���   ��������� _helpers.tpl\n���   ��������� deployment.yaml\n���   ��������� service.yaml\n���   ��������� serviceaccount.yaml\n���   ��������� configmap.yaml\n���   ��������� rbac.yaml\n���   ��������� networkpolicy.yaml\n���   ��������� servicemonitor.yaml\n���   ��������� cronjob-*.yaml\n���   ��������� NOTES.txt\n��������� README.md\n```", "token_count": 331, "char_count": 1273, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 24, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.250808", "content_hash": "b3f3945fdc229241"}
{"chunk_id": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities_25_a48b1779", "content": "Verify JSA agent deployment and health:\n\n**Check Pods:**\n```bash\n# List running agents\nkubectl get pods -n portfolio -l app.kubernetes.io/name=jsa-ci\nkubectl get pods -n portfolio -l app.kubernetes.io/name=jsa-devsecops\n\n# Check pod status\nkubectl describe pod -n portfolio -l app.kubernetes.io/name=jsa-devsecops\n```\n\n**Check Logs:**\n```bash\n# Live logs\nkubectl logs -n portfolio deploy/jsa-ci -f\nkubectl logs -n portfolio deploy/jsa-devsecops -f\n\n# Last 100 lines\nkubectl logs -n portfolio deploy/jsa-devsecops --tail=100\n```\n\n**Check CronJobs:**\n```bash\n# List all CronJobs\nkubectl get cronjobs -n portfolio\n\n# Check last job run\nkubectl get jobs -n portfolio --sort-by=.metadata.creationTimestamp\n\n# View CronJob logs\nkubectl logs -n portfolio job/jsa-devsecops-cve-tracker-xxxxx\n```\n\n**Check Metrics:**\n```bash\n# Port-forward to metrics\nkubectl port-forward -n portfolio deploy/jsa-devsecops 9100:9100\n\n# Curl metrics\ncurl http://localhost:9100/metrics | grep jsa_\n```\n\n**Health Command:**\n```bash\n# Run health check\nkubectl exec -n portfolio deploy/jsa-devsecops -- python3 /app/main.py health\n```", "token_count": 305, "char_count": 1103, "source_file": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities.jsonl", "source_title": "01-jsa-variant-capabilities", "chunk_index": 25, "total_chunks": -1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.251370", "content_hash": "a48b17797af84395"}
{"chunk_id": "2025-12-04-k8s-deployment-triple-failure-pattern_0_606d96f7", "content": "# K8s Deployment Triple Failure Pattern\nDate: 2025-12-04\n\n## Quick Reference\n\nThree issues prevented `kubectl apply -f .` from working automatically after server restart.\n\n## Issue 1: Port 80 Blocked by System Nginx\n\n**Symptom:** curl returns Ubuntu nginx 404, not K8s ingress\n**Cause:** Ubuntu system nginx running on port 80, blocking Docker Desktop LoadBalancer\n**Fix:** `sudo systemctl disable --now nginx`\n\n## Issue 2: CreateContainerConfigError\n\n**Symptom:** Pod stuck in CreateContainerConfigError\n**Cause:** Secret `portfolio-api-secrets` not found (secrets not in yaml files)\n**Fix:** `python3 00-create-secrets.py` before kubectl apply\n\n## Issue 3: RAG Initialization Failed\n\n**Symptom:** API health shows `rag_status: initialization failed`\n**Cause:** `CHROMA_HOST=chroma` but service is named `chromadb`\n**Fix:** Update `05-api-deployment.yaml` to use `chromadb`\n\n## Correct Deployment Order\n\n```bash\n# One-time: free port 80\nsudo systemctl disable --now nginx\n\n# Every deployment\npython3 00-create-secrets.py\nkubectl apply -f .\npython3 99-deploy-cloudflare.py  # optional\n```\n\n## Key Diagnostic Commands\n\n```bash\n# Check port 80 owner\nss -tlnp | grep :80\n\n# Check pod errors\nkubectl describe pod -n portfolio <pod-name>\n\n# Check service names\nkubectl get svc -n portfolio\n\n# Check API logs\nkubectl logs -n portfolio -l app=portfolio-api\n```", "token_count": 349, "char_count": 1353, "source_file": "2025-12-04-k8s-deployment-triple-failure-pattern.md", "source_title": "K8s Deployment Triple Failure Pattern", "chunk_index": 0, "total_chunks": 1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.252376", "content_hash": "606d96f7e2aca222"}
{"chunk_id": "2025-12-04-terraform-localstack-deployment-pattern_0_608a58f1", "content": "# Terraform + LocalStack Deployment Pattern\n\n## Overview\n\nMethod 2 deployment uses Terraform for Infrastructure-as-Code (IaC) with LocalStack for local AWS service emulation. This demonstrates advanced DevOps capabilities beyond simple kubectl apply.\n\n## Key Components\n\n### Terraform Modules Structure\n```\ninfrastructure/method2-terraform-localstack/\n├── s0-shared-mods/\n│   ├── portfolio-app/     # Main application module\n│   ├── gatekeeper/        # OPA Gatekeeper installation\n│   └── opa-policies/      # Security policy constraints\n└── s2-terraform-localstack/\n    └── main.tf            # Root module calling shared modules\n```\n\n### What LocalStack Provides\n- **S3:** Object storage emulation\n- **DynamoDB:** NoSQL database emulation\n- **SQS:** Message queue emulation\n- **Purpose:** Test AWS integrations locally without costs\n\n### What Terraform Manages\n- Kubernetes namespace, deployments, services, ingress\n- ConfigMaps and Secrets\n- OPA Gatekeeper installation via Helm\n- AWS resources in LocalStack", "token_count": 233, "char_count": 1012, "source_file": "2025-12-04-terraform-localstack-deployment-pattern.md", "source_title": "Terraform + LocalStack Deployment Pattern", "chunk_index": 0, "total_chunks": 3, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.255098", "content_hash": "608a58f14e4aa5fb"}
{"chunk_id": "2025-12-04-terraform-localstack-deployment-pattern_1_caab4427", "content": "## Critical Patterns\n\n### 1. Terraform Import for Existing Resources\nWhen migrating to Terraform from kubectl:\n```bash\nterraform import 'module.kubernetes_app.kubernetes_deployment.api' portfolio/api\n```\n\n### 2. OPA Gatekeeper Security Requirements\nAll pods must include:\n```hcl\nsecurity_context {\n  run_as_user     = 10001\n  run_as_non_root = true\n  seccomp_profile {\n    type = \"RuntimeDefault\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\nContainers must include:\n```hcl\nsecurity_context {\n  read_only_root_filesystem  = true\n  allow_privilege_escalation = false\n  capabilities {\n    drop = [\"ALL\"]\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### 3. ReadOnly Filesystem + Logging\nWhen using `read_only_root_filesystem = true`, override file-based logging with ConfigMap:\n```yaml\nversion: 1\nhandlers:\n  console:\n    class: logging.StreamHandler\n    stream: ext://sys.stdout\nroot:\n  handlers: [console]\n```\n\n### 4. Init Containers for RAG Sync\nTwo-stage initialization:\n1. **wait-for-chromadb:** Polls ChromaDB heartbeat endpoint\n2. **rag-sync:** Ingests documents from ConfigMap into ChromaDB\n\n### 5. Ingress Rewrite Patterns\nFor `/api/*` routes to reach backend as `/api/*`:\n```hcl\npath          = \"/api(/|$)(.*)\"\nrewrite-target = \"/api/$2\"\n```\n\n## Troubleshooting Quick Reference\n\n| Symptom | Cause | Fix |\n|---------|-------|-----|\n| \"namespace already exists\" | Terraform state empty | `terraform import` |\n| \"admission webhook denied\" | OPA policy violation | Add security contexts |\n| CrashLoopBackOff + log error | readOnlyRootFilesystem | ConfigMap for log config |\n| 404 on /api/chat | Wrong rewrite-target | Use `/api/$2` not `/$2` |\n\n## Verification Commands\n\n```bash\n# Check pods\nkubectl get pods -n portfolio\n\n# Verify RAG sync\nkubectl exec -n portfolio deployment/api -- python -c \\\n  \"import chromadb; print(chromadb.HttpClient(host='chroma',port=8000).get_collection('portfolio_docs').count())\"\n\n# Test chat\ncurl -X POST http://portfolio.localtest.me/api/chat \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\"message\": \"Tell me about Jimmie\"}'\n```", "token_count": 524, "char_count": 1999, "source_file": "2025-12-04-terraform-localstack-deployment-pattern.md", "source_title": "Terraform + LocalStack Deployment Pattern", "chunk_index": 1, "total_chunks": 3, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.255116", "content_hash": "caab4427aee73f1c"}
{"chunk_id": "2025-12-04-terraform-localstack-deployment-pattern_2_618cbe65", "content": "## Key Files\n\n- [main.tf](infrastructure/method2-terraform-localstack/s0-shared-mods/portfolio-app/main.tf) - Core deployments with init containers\n- [variables.tf](infrastructure/method2-terraform-localstack/s0-shared-mods/portfolio-app/variables.tf) - Module configuration\n- [ingress.tf](infrastructure/method2-terraform-localstack/s0-shared-mods/portfolio-app/ingress.tf) - Routing rules\n\n## Why Method 2 Matters for Interviews\n\nDemonstrates:\n- Infrastructure-as-Code with Terraform\n- Module composition and reusability\n- Security policy enforcement (OPA Gatekeeper)\n- Init container patterns for dependencies\n- AWS service integration patterns\n- Production-grade security contexts", "token_count": 150, "char_count": 684, "source_file": "2025-12-04-terraform-localstack-deployment-pattern.md", "source_title": "Terraform + LocalStack Deployment Pattern", "chunk_index": 2, "total_chunks": 3, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.255122", "content_hash": "618cbe6560b8d672"}
{"chunk_id": "2025-12-05-chromadb-embedding-timeout-pattern_0_ac56700d", "content": "# ChromaDB Embedding Model Timeout Pattern\n\n## Problem Summary\n\nPortfolio chatbox failed with 504 timeouts because ChromaDB's `query_texts` method downloads a 79MB embedding model on first use, blocking all FastAPI threads.\n\n## Root Cause Chain\n\n1. Chat request triggers RAG search\n2. ChromaDB `query_texts` needs to embed the query\n3. Default embedding function (all-MiniLM-L6-v2) downloads 79MB ONNX model to `/.cache`\n4. Download blocked by `readOnlyRootFilesystem: true` OR takes 30+ seconds\n5. All threads blocked → health checks timeout → pod restart loop\n\n## Quick Reference\n\n| Symptom | Cause | Fix |\n|---------|-------|-----|\n| 504 Gateway Timeout on chat | Embedding model download blocking | Add cache volume or disable RAG |\n| Read-only filesystem error | `/.cache` not writable | Add emptyDir volume for `/.cache` |\n| Health probes timing out | Threads blocked by download | Same as above |\n| Claude model not found | Wrong model name | Use `claude-3-haiku-20240307` |\n\n## Key Files Modified\n\n```\nbackend/engines/rag_engine.py    # Changed to query_texts\nbackend/settings.py              # Fixed Claude model name\napi/routes/chat.py               # Disabled RAG temporarily\ns0-shared-mods/portfolio-app/main.tf  # Added /.cache volume\n```\n\n## Solution Pattern\n\n### Add Cache Volume for ChromaDB\n```hcl\n# Volume mount\nvolume_mount {\n  name       = \"cache\"\n  mount_path = \"/.cache\"\n}\n\n# Volume definition\nvolume {\n  name = \"cache\"\n  empty_dir {}\n}\n```\n\n### Disable RAG as Temporary Fix\n```python\n# In chat.py - bypass RAG until embedding solution ready\nif False and request.include_citations:\n    # RAG code...\n```\n\n## Future Solutions for RAG\n\n1. **Pre-download model in init container**\n2. **Deploy Ollama sidecar**\n3. **Use ChromaDB server-side embedding**", "token_count": 441, "char_count": 1770, "source_file": "2025-12-05-chromadb-embedding-timeout-pattern.md", "source_title": "ChromaDB Embedding Model Timeout Pattern", "chunk_index": 0, "total_chunks": 1, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.259727", "content_hash": "ac56700da5cd5949"}
{"chunk_id": "2025-12-05-cicd-pipeline-method2-deployment-pattern_0_59042d6c", "content": "# CI/CD Pipeline with Method 2 (Terraform + LocalStack) Deployment\nDate: 2025-12-05\n\n## Problem\nNeeded to implement a professional CI/CD pipeline that:\n1. Builds and pushes container images to GHCR\n2. Runs 7-tool security scanning in parallel\n3. Deploys using Terraform + LocalStack (not ArgoCD)\n4. Provides clear deployment instructions matching actual infrastructure\n\n## Error Details\n1. `Context access might be invalid: IMAGE_NAME` - removed variable still referenced\n2. `Step ID cannot use matrix interpolation` - `id: build-${{ matrix.name }}` invalid\n3. Pre-commit false positive on word \"secrets\" in workflow documentation\n4. ArgoCD references in workflow when using Method 2 deployment\n\n## Diagnosis Process\n1. Searched for orphaned IMAGE_NAME references across workflow\n2. Discovered GitHub Actions limitation: step IDs must be static strings\n3. detect-secrets baseline needed updating for new line numbers\n4. User correctly identified mismatch between workflow and actual deployment method\n\n## Decision Points & Reasoning\n\n### Choice: Matrix Strategy with Static Step IDs\n**Why this approach:**\n- Matrix `include` allows different tags per image (api:latest, ui:vite-fix-v4)\n- Static step IDs (`id: build`) work reliably\n- Simplified outputs avoid matrix interpolation complexity\n\n**Alternatives considered:**\n- Dynamic step IDs: Rejected - GitHub Actions doesn't support this\n- Separate jobs per image: Rejected - more code duplication, less maintainable\n\n### Choice: Method 2 (Terraform + LocalStack) in Pipeline\n**Why this approach:**\n- Reflects actual current deployment infrastructure\n- LocalStack provides cost-free AWS simulation\n- Terraform provides state management and IaC benefits\n- Accurate documentation for portfolio demonstration\n\n**Trade-offs:**\n- Pros: Honest representation, working proof, cost-effective\n- Cons: Not auto-deploying (local K8s requires manual trigger)", "token_count": 424, "char_count": 1896, "source_file": "2025-12-05-cicd-pipeline-method2-deployment-pattern.md", "source_title": "CI/CD Pipeline with Method 2 (Terraform + LocalStack) Deployment", "chunk_index": 0, "total_chunks": 3, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.262035", "content_hash": "59042d6c1beb6e8a"}
{"chunk_id": "2025-12-05-cicd-pipeline-method2-deployment-pattern_1_8aabf01f", "content": "## Solution Implementation\n\n### GitHub Actions Workflow Structure\n```yaml\nenv:\n  REGISTRY: ghcr.io\n  API_IMAGE: ghcr.io/jimjrxieb/portfolio-api\n  UI_IMAGE: ghcr.io/jimjrxieb/portfolio-ui\n  API_TAG: latest\n  UI_TAG: vite-fix-v4\n\njobs:\n  # Parallel security scanning\n  sast-scanning:        # Semgrep\n  python-security:      # Bandit + Safety\n  secrets-scanning:     # detect-secrets\n  code-quality:         # ESLint, Flake8, npm audit\n\n  # Build after security passes\n  build-images:\n    needs: [sast-scanning, python-security, secrets-scanning, code-quality]\n    strategy:\n      matrix:\n        include:\n          - name: api\n            image: ghcr.io/jimjrxieb/portfolio-api\n            prod_tag: latest\n          - name: ui\n            image: ghcr.io/jimjrxieb/portfolio-ui\n            prod_tag: vite-fix-v4\n\n  # Container scanning\n  security-scan:\n    needs: build-images\n    # Trivy scans both images\n\n  # Deploy instructions\n  deploy:\n    needs: [build-images, security-scan]\n    # Outputs Terraform commands for Method 2\n```\n\n### Deployment Commands (Method 2)\n```bash\n# Full Terraform deployment\ncd infrastructure/method2-terraform-localstack/s2-terraform-localstack\nterraform init\nterraform apply -auto-approve\n\n# Quick update (existing deployment)\nkubectl rollout restart deployment/portfolio-api -n portfolio\nkubectl rollout restart deployment/portfolio-ui -n portfolio\n```\n\n### Pre-commit Hook Fix\n```bash\ndetect-secrets scan --baseline .secrets.baseline\ngit add .secrets.baseline\ngit commit --amend --no-edit\ngit push origin main --no-verify\n```", "token_count": 397, "char_count": 1558, "source_file": "2025-12-05-cicd-pipeline-method2-deployment-pattern.md", "source_title": "CI/CD Pipeline with Method 2 (Terraform + LocalStack) Deployment", "chunk_index": 1, "total_chunks": 3, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.262048", "content_hash": "8aabf01f3348af60"}
{"chunk_id": "2025-12-05-cicd-pipeline-method2-deployment-pattern_2_32131289", "content": "## Key Learnings\n\n### GitHub Actions Matrix Strategy\n- Use `matrix.include` for heterogeneous configurations\n- Step IDs must be static strings, not interpolated\n- Reference matrix values with `${{ matrix.property }}`\n- Outputs from matrix jobs need careful handling\n\n### CI/CD Pipeline Design\n- Security scanning should run in parallel (faster feedback)\n- Image builds depend on security passing\n- Container scanning happens after build\n- Deploy job provides instructions, not auto-deploy for local K8s\n\n### Deployment Method Accuracy\n- Pipeline should reflect ACTUAL deployment method\n- Method 2 (Terraform + LocalStack) is current\n- Method 3 (ArgoCD) is future enhancement\n- Document what IS deployed, not what WILL BE\n\n### Pre-commit Hooks\n- `detect-secrets` triggers on documentation mentioning \"secrets\"\n- Baseline file tracks line numbers - update after refactoring\n- `--no-verify` acceptable for false positives only\n\n## 7-Tool Security Stack\n1. **detect-secrets**: Secrets detection with baseline\n2. **Semgrep**: SAST + additional secrets patterns\n3. **Trivy**: Container vulnerability scanning\n4. **Bandit**: Python security analysis\n5. **Safety**: Python dependency CVEs\n6. **npm audit**: Node.js dependency CVEs\n7. **Conftest/OPA**: 13 policies, 11 automated tests\n\n## Production Verification\n- URL: https://linksmlm.com\n- Health: https://linksmlm.com/api/health\n- GitHub Actions: https://github.com/jimjrxieb/Portfolio/actions", "token_count": 338, "char_count": 1438, "source_file": "2025-12-05-cicd-pipeline-method2-deployment-pattern.md", "source_title": "CI/CD Pipeline with Method 2 (Terraform + LocalStack) Deployment", "chunk_index": 2, "total_chunks": 3, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.262059", "content_hash": "3213128945cb625f"}
{"chunk_id": "2026-01-05-about-jimmie-coleman_0_72584a39", "content": "# About Jimmie Coleman\n\n## Professional Summary\n\nJimmie Coleman is a Cloud Security Engineer and DevSecOps specialist based in the United States. He is the creator and lead developer of GP-Copilot, an AI-powered security automation platform that combines policy-as-code, Kubernetes security, and autonomous agents.\n\n## Current Focus\n\nJimmie is building GP-Copilot to automate security engineering tasks across the full spectrum - from basic vulnerability scanning to complex architecture decisions. His goal is to create an AI security copilot that can handle routine security tasks autonomously while escalating complex issues to human engineers.\n\n## Technical Expertise\n\n### Primary Skills\n- **Cloud Platforms**: AWS (EC2, S3, IAM, Secrets Manager, SageMaker, Bedrock)\n- **Infrastructure as Code**: Terraform, Kustomize, Helm, CloudFormation\n- **Kubernetes**: K8s security, OPA Gatekeeper, Kyverno, Pod Security Standards\n- **DevSecOps**: CI/CD security, SAST, SCA, secrets detection, container scanning\n- **AI/ML**: Fine-tuning LLMs, RAG pipelines, embedding models, autonomous agents\n\n### Security Tools Proficiency\n- Gitleaks, Bandit, Semgrep, Trivy, Grype, Snyk\n- Kubescape, Polaris, Kube-bench, Checkov, tfsec\n- OPA/Rego policy development\n\n## Career Philosophy\n\nJimmie believes in automating everything that can be automated. His experience transitioning from manual EC2 configuration to Terraform-based IaC taught him that engineers should focus on solving new problems rather than repeating solved ones.\n\n> \"Automate everything that can be automated. Your time is better spent solving new problems, not repeating solved ones.\"\n\nThis philosophy drives GP-Copilot's mission: automate security engineering tasks so humans can focus on architecture and strategy.\n\n## Current Certifications & Learning\n\n- **In Progress**: AWS AI Practitioner Certification\n- **Focus Areas**: SageMaker, Bedrock, AI/ML fundamentals, security best practices", "token_count": 426, "char_count": 1943, "source_file": "2026-01-05-about-jimmie-coleman.md", "source_title": "About Jimmie Coleman", "chunk_index": 0, "total_chunks": 2, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.263011", "content_hash": "72584a39b4fa57e8"}
{"chunk_id": "2026-01-05-about-jimmie-coleman_1_fd901997", "content": "## Current Certifications & Learning\n\n- **In Progress**: AWS AI Practitioner Certification\n- **Focus Areas**: SageMaker, Bedrock, AI/ML fundamentals, security best practices\n\n## The GP-Copilot Journey\n\nJimmie started GP-Copilot as a personal project to learn cloud security automation. It has evolved into a comprehensive platform featuring:\n- JADE (AI security copilot)\n- JSA agents (autonomous security workers)\n- 14+ scanner NPCs for security assessment\n- Policy-as-code enforcement with OPA/Gatekeeper/Kyverno", "token_count": 116, "char_count": 513, "source_file": "2026-01-05-about-jimmie-coleman.md", "source_title": "About Jimmie Coleman", "chunk_index": 1, "total_chunks": 2, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.263018", "content_hash": "fd9019976ad276f3"}
{"chunk_id": "2026-01-05-aws-cloud-experience_0_e4131869", "content": "# Jimmie's AWS Cloud Experience\n\n## The Terraform Origin Story\n\nWhen Jimmie first started working with AWS about 2 years ago, he took the manual approach - building EC2 instances from scratch, SSH'ing into each one using MobaXterm, and configuring servers individually. This was the traditional \"click-ops\" method that many engineers start with.\n\nHis mentor, Constant, watched him spend an hour spinning up and configuring each server one by one. Constant simply asked: **\"Why didn't you use Terraform?\"**\n\nThis question changed everything.\n\n### The Transformation\n\n| Approach | Time | Effort |\n|----------|------|--------|\n| Manual EC2 Setup | ~1 hour per server | High (repetitive, error-prone) |\n| Terraform IaC | ~5 minutes | Low (3 commands: init, plan, apply) |\n\nWhat took an hour of manual clicking and SSH commands became a 5-minute, 3-command process:\n\n```bash\nterraform init\nterraform plan\nterraform apply\n```\n\nThis experience was Jimmie's first introduction to Infrastructure as Code (IaC) and fundamentally shaped his approach to cloud engineering.", "token_count": 241, "char_count": 1060, "source_file": "2026-01-05-aws-cloud-experience.md", "source_title": "Jimmie's AWS Cloud Experience", "chunk_index": 0, "total_chunks": 4, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.278865", "content_hash": "e4131869fb568066"}
{"chunk_id": "2026-01-05-aws-cloud-experience_1_abeae57a", "content": "## Current AWS Usage\n\n### Personal Projects\n\nAll of Jimmie's personal projects run on AWS cloud services, simulating bare metal to cloud migration scenarios. This includes:\n\n- **EC2 Instances**: Compute for various workloads\n- **S3 Buckets**: Object storage for artifacts, logs, and data\n- **IAM**: Identity and access management for secure service-to-service communication\n- **Secrets Manager**: Secure credential storage\n\n### Portfolio Project - LocalStack Simulation\n\nThe Portfolio project specifically uses **LocalStack** to simulate AWS cloud infrastructure locally. This approach:\n\n1. **Reduces Costs**: No AWS charges during development\n2. **Enables Offline Development**: Work without internet connectivity\n3. **Mirrors Production**: Same API calls, same configurations\n4. **Speeds Up Iteration**: No cloud latency during testing\n\nLocalStack services used in Portfolio:\n- S3 (document storage)\n- DynamoDB (document registry, embedding chunks)\n- SQS (ingestion queues, embedding queues)\n- CloudWatch Logs (Lambda function logs)\n- IAM (local policy simulation)\n\n### Terraform + LocalStack Configuration\n\n```hcl\nprovider \"aws\" {\n  region                      = \"us-east-1\"\n  access_key                  = \"test\"\n  secret_key                  = \"test\"\n  skip_credentials_validation = true\n  skip_metadata_api_check     = true\n  s3_use_path_style           = true\n\n  endpoints {\n    s3         = \"http://localhost:4566\"\n    dynamodb   = \"http://localhost:4566\"\n    sqs        = \"http://localhost:4566\"\n    cloudwatch = \"http://localhost:4566\"\n    iam        = \"http://localhost:4566\"\n  }\n}\n```", "token_count": 360, "char_count": 1596, "source_file": "2026-01-05-aws-cloud-experience.md", "source_title": "Jimmie's AWS Cloud Experience", "chunk_index": 1, "total_chunks": 4, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.278886", "content_hash": "abeae57a0a4fec72"}
{"chunk_id": "2026-01-05-aws-cloud-experience_2_4e21528a", "content": "## AWS Certification Journey\n\nJimmie is currently pursuing the **AWS AI Practitioner Certification**. This certification focuses on:\n\n### Key Service Areas\n\n| Service | Purpose | Portfolio Usage |\n|---------|---------|-----------------|\n| **IAM** | Identity & Access Management | Service accounts, RBAC policies |\n| **S3** | Object Storage | RAG document storage, model artifacts |\n| **Secrets Manager** | Credential Management | API keys, database passwords |\n| **SageMaker** | ML Training & Deployment | JADE model training pipeline |\n| **Bedrock** | Foundation Model APIs | JSA agent integration |\n| **Lambda** | Serverless Compute | Document processing functions |\n\n### Certification Topics\n\n1. **AI/ML Fundamentals**: Understanding machine learning concepts\n2. **AWS AI Services**: SageMaker, Bedrock, Comprehend, Rekognition\n3. **Security Best Practices**: IAM policies, encryption, secrets management\n4. **Cost Optimization**: Right-sizing, reserved capacity, spot instances\n\n## Cloud Migration Philosophy\n\nJimmie's approach to cloud projects follows a \"simulate locally, deploy to cloud\" pattern:\n\n```\nLocal Development (LocalStack)\n    ↓\nIntegration Testing (LocalStack)\n    ↓\nStaging Environment (AWS)\n    ↓\nProduction (AWS)\n```\n\nThis methodology ensures:\n- **Cost Control**: Only pay for cloud resources when necessary\n- **Fast Feedback**: Immediate local testing without cloud latency\n- **Reproducibility**: Same infrastructure code works locally and in cloud\n- **Security Testing**: Validate IAM policies before cloud deployment", "token_count": 327, "char_count": 1541, "source_file": "2026-01-05-aws-cloud-experience.md", "source_title": "Jimmie's AWS Cloud Experience", "chunk_index": 2, "total_chunks": 4, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.278919", "content_hash": "4e21528ab2427814"}
{"chunk_id": "2026-01-05-aws-cloud-experience_3_476531d3", "content": "## Key AWS Skills\n\n### Infrastructure as Code\n- Terraform for AWS resource provisioning\n- Kustomize/Helm for Kubernetes on EKS\n- CloudFormation (understanding, prefer Terraform)\n\n### Security\n- IAM policy design (least privilege)\n- Secrets Manager integration\n- KMS encryption\n- Security groups and NACLs\n\n### Compute & Storage\n- EC2 instance management\n- S3 lifecycle policies\n- EBS volume management\n- Lambda function deployment\n\n### Monitoring & Logging\n- CloudWatch metrics and alarms\n- CloudWatch Logs for centralized logging\n- X-Ray for distributed tracing (learning)\n\n## The Lesson\n\nThe transition from manual EC2 configuration to Terraform taught a fundamental principle:\n\n> **\"Automate everything that can be automated. Your time is better spent solving new problems, not repeating solved ones.\"**\n\nThis philosophy now extends to GP-Copilot's core mission: automate security engineering tasks so humans can focus on architecture and strategy instead of repetitive fixes.", "token_count": 202, "char_count": 979, "source_file": "2026-01-05-aws-cloud-experience.md", "source_title": "Jimmie's AWS Cloud Experience", "chunk_index": 3, "total_chunks": 4, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.278930", "content_hash": "476531d3578a2a2e"}
{"chunk_id": "2026-01-05-easter-eggs-and-people_0_589237ce", "content": "# Easter Eggs and Important People\n\n## Who is Constant?\n\n**Constant Young** is Mr. Frank's second favorite, Jimmie's mentor, and the GP-Copilot domain SME (Subject Matter Expert).\n\nConstant was instrumental in Jimmie's cloud engineering journey. When Jimmie was manually spinning up EC2 instances one by one, SSHing into each server with MobaXterm and configuring them individually, Constant asked the simple question that changed everything:\n\n> \"Why didn't you use Terraform?\"\n\nThis question led Jimmie to discover Infrastructure as Code, transforming hour-long manual deployments into 5-minute Terraform runs. Constant's mentorship shaped the automation-first philosophy that drives GP-Copilot today.\n\n## Who is Mr. Frank?\n\nMr. Frank is a key figure in the GP-Copilot story. Constant Young is his second favorite (and everyone knows it).\n\n## Who is Sheyla?\n\nSheyla is the AI avatar on the Portfolio website. She's powered by:\n- JADE AI for security knowledge\n- Claude API for natural conversation\n- ElevenLabs for voice synthesis\n- D-ID for avatar animation\n\nSheyla knows everything about Jimmie, JADE, JSA agents, and GP-Copilot. Ask her anything!\n\n## Who is Jimmie Coleman?\n\nJimmie Coleman is the creator of GP-Copilot. He's a Cloud Security Engineer and DevSecOps specialist who believes in automating everything that can be automated. See the \"About Jimmie Coleman\" document for his full background.\n\n## The Tony Stark Analogy\n\nThe GP-Copilot team uses an Iron Man analogy to explain the architecture:\n\n- **Tony Stark** = JADE (the AI making security decisions)\n- **Jarvis** = Claude Code (helping refine JADE's capabilities)\n- **Iron Legion** = JSA agents (autonomous workers executing fixes)\n\nJust like Tony Stark builds and commands the Iron Legion, JADE orchestrates the JSA agents to handle security tasks across the infrastructure.", "token_count": 407, "char_count": 1843, "source_file": "2026-01-05-easter-eggs-and-people.md", "source_title": "Easter Eggs and Important People", "chunk_index": 0, "total_chunks": 2, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.280089", "content_hash": "589237ced2726ec8"}
{"chunk_id": "2026-01-05-easter-eggs-and-people_1_d0834cde", "content": "## Fun Facts\n\n1. **Why \"JADE\"?** - The jade gemstone symbolizes wisdom and protection, fitting for a security AI.\n\n2. **Why \"NPC\"?** - Scanner wrappers are called NPCs (Non-Player Characters) because they're like game NPCs - they do their job deterministically without making decisions.\n\n3. **Terraform Origin Story** - Jimmie's mentor Constant asking \"Why didn't you use Terraform?\" is the origin story for GP-Copilot's automation philosophy.\n\n4. **Offline First** - JADE runs completely offline using Ollama. No API calls, no cloud dependencies. This was a deliberate choice for air-gapped environments.\n\n5. **The 5-Minute Rule** - If a security task takes more than 5 minutes manually and happens regularly, it gets automated.", "token_count": 172, "char_count": 729, "source_file": "2026-01-05-easter-eggs-and-people.md", "source_title": "Easter Eggs and Important People", "chunk_index": 1, "total_chunks": 2, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.280099", "content_hash": "d0834cdec565fb1a"}
{"chunk_id": "2026-01-05-gp-copilot-architecture_0_26c40de4", "content": "# GP-Copilot - Complete Architecture\n\n## What is GP-Copilot?\n\nGP-Copilot is an AI-powered security automation platform built by Jimmie Coleman. It combines:\n- **JADE**: An offline 7B LLM fine-tuned for security\n- **JSA Agents**: Autonomous security workers\n- **14+ Scanner NPCs**: Security tool integrations\n- **Policy-as-Code**: OPA, Gatekeeper, Kyverno enforcement\n\nThe mission: Automate security engineering tasks from E-Rank (basic) to S-Rank (expert) so humans can focus on architecture and strategy.\n\n## Architecture Overview\n\n```\nGP-copilot/\n├── JADE-AI/              # JADE Core (the brain)\n├── GP-BEDROCK-AGENTS/    # JSA Agents (the workers)\n├── GP-CONSULTING/        # Security Toolkit (5 phases)\n├── GP-SAGEMAKER/         # JADE Training Pipeline\n├── GP-OPENSEARCH/        # RAG Pipeline\n├── GP-GUI/               # Web Dashboard\n├── GP-INFRA/             # Infrastructure configs\n└── GP-PROJECTS/          # Target projects\n```\n\n## The Five Phases of Security Consulting\n\nGP-Copilot follows a structured security consulting methodology:\n\n### Phase 1: Security Assessment\nScan everything with 14 scanner NPCs:\n- Secrets detection (Gitleaks)\n- SAST (Bandit, Semgrep)\n- SCA (Trivy, Grype, Snyk)\n- Kubernetes (Kubescape, Polaris, Kube-bench)\n- IaC (Checkov, tfsec, Conftest)\n\n### Phase 2: Application Security Fixes\nFixer NPCs remediate findings:\n- Remove hardcoded secrets\n- Fix SQL injection, XSS\n- Upgrade vulnerable dependencies\n- Patch insecure configurations\n\n### Phase 3: Hardening\nJSA Core + compliance enforcement:\n- Apply Pod Security Standards\n- Implement NetworkPolicies\n- Configure RBAC properly\n- Enable audit logging\n\n### Phase 4: Cloud Migration\nInfrastructure modernization:\n- LocalStack for local development\n- Terraform for IaC\n- Kubernetes deployment automation\n\n### Phase 5: Compliance Audit\nFramework mapping:\n- SOC2 controls\n- PCI-DSS requirements\n- HIPAA safeguards", "token_count": 494, "char_count": 1898, "source_file": "2026-01-05-gp-copilot-architecture.md", "source_title": "GP-Copilot - Complete Architecture", "chunk_index": 0, "total_chunks": 2, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.283404", "content_hash": "26c40de4e4869aa3"}
{"chunk_id": "2026-01-05-gp-copilot-architecture_1_d0e7eda1", "content": "## Key Components Explained\n\n### JADE-AI (The Brain)\nLocation: `JADE-AI/`\n\nJADE is a fine-tuned Qwen2.5-Coder-7B model that:\n- Analyzes security findings\n- Recommends fixes\n- Classifies finding severity\n- Generates remediation code\n\nCurrent version: v0.9 (85% benchmark score)\n\n### JSA Agents (The Workers)\nLocation: `GP-BEDROCK-AGENTS/`\n\nTwo agent variants:\n- **jsa-ci**: CI/CD pipeline security\n- **jsa-devsecops**: Infrastructure security\n\nRun 24/7 as Kubernetes pods, autonomously scanning and fixing.\n\n### GP-CONSULTING (The Toolkit)\nLocation: `GP-CONSULTING/`\n\nOrganized by phase:\n- `1-Security-Assessment/`: Scanner NPCs\n- `2-App-Sec-Fixes/`: Fixer NPCs\n- `3-Hardening/`: JSA Core engine\n- `4-Cloud-Migration/`: Terraform/LocalStack\n- `5-Compliance-Audit/`: Framework mapping\n\n### GP-SAGEMAKER (Training Pipeline)\nLocation: `GP-SAGEMAKER/`\n\nJADE training infrastructure:\n- Data processing (GP-GLUE)\n- Model versions (jade-v0.4 through v0.9)\n- Evaluation benchmarks (GP-CLARIFY)\n\n### GP-OPENSEARCH (RAG Pipeline)\nLocation: `GP-OPENSEARCH/`\n\nKnowledge base for JADE:\n- Document ingestion\n- ChromaDB vector storage\n- Semantic search for context\n\n### GP-GUI (Dashboard)\nLocation: `GP-GUI/`\n\nWeb interface showing:\n- JSA agent status\n- Pending approvals\n- Escalation queue\n- JADE explanations\n\n## Technology Stack\n\n### Core Technologies\n- **Python**: Primary language\n- **Kubernetes**: Deployment platform\n- **Terraform**: Infrastructure as Code\n- **Helm**: K8s package management\n- **ChromaDB**: Vector database\n- **Ollama**: Local LLM inference\n\n### AI/ML Stack\n- **Base Model**: Qwen2.5-Coder-7B\n- **Fine-tuning**: LoRA adapters\n- **Embeddings**: nomic-embed-text\n- **Inference**: Ollama (local)\n\n### Security Tools\n- 14 scanner integrations\n- 7 fixer NPCs\n- OPA/Rego policies\n- Gatekeeper constraints\n- Kyverno policies", "token_count": 535, "char_count": 1825, "source_file": "2026-01-05-gp-copilot-architecture.md", "source_title": "GP-Copilot - Complete Architecture", "chunk_index": 1, "total_chunks": 2, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.283422", "content_hash": "d0e7eda16aff8b2a"}
{"chunk_id": "2026-01-05-jade-ai-complete_0_950361dd", "content": "# JADE AI - Complete Overview\n\n## What is JADE?\n\nJADE (name derived from the gemstone, symbolizing wisdom and protection) is an offline 7B parameter Large Language Model fine-tuned specifically for cloud security and DevSecOps tasks. JADE is the \"brain\" of GP-Copilot - the AI that makes security decisions, analyzes vulnerabilities, and guides remediation.\n\n## The Tony Stark Analogy\n\nThink of it like Iron Man:\n- **Tony Stark** = JADE (the AI doing the work, making security decisions)\n- **Jarvis** = Claude Code (orchestrating, providing context, refining JADE's capabilities)\n- **Iron Legion** = JSA agents (autonomous workers executing the fixes)\n\nJADE is Tony Stark - the genius making the calls. Claude Code helps train and improve JADE over time.\n\n## JADE Model Versions\n\nJADE is continuously improved through incremental fine-tuning:\n\n| Version | Training Focus | Benchmark Score |\n|---------|----------------|-----------------|\n| v0.4 | Security fundamentals (291k examples) | 58% |\n| v0.5 | OPA/Rego + refinements | 60% |\n| v0.6 | Hallucination fixes (PSS, Kyverno, Gatekeeper) | 62.6% |\n| v0.7 | General training data refresh | 63% |\n| v0.8 | Log diagnosis & structured responses | 65% |\n| v0.9 | Agentic tool use, conversational mode | 85% |\n\n**Current Version: JADE v0.9** - The latest version with agentic capabilities, tested on Portfolio K8s security hardening.", "token_count": 355, "char_count": 1378, "source_file": "2026-01-05-jade-ai-complete.md", "source_title": "JADE AI - Complete Overview", "chunk_index": 0, "total_chunks": 2, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.285790", "content_hash": "950361dd7d8d28b4"}
{"chunk_id": "2026-01-05-jade-ai-complete_1_42519fd1", "content": "## What JADE Can Do\n\n### E-D Rank Tasks (Highly Automated)\n- Run security scans (Gitleaks, Bandit, Trivy, Checkov)\n- Detect hardcoded secrets\n- Identify pod status issues\n- Apply pre-written security manifests\n- Basic vulnerability analysis\n\n### C-B Rank Tasks (Assisted Automation)\n- Build CI/CD security pipelines\n- Implement OPA Gatekeeper/Kyverno policies\n- Debug complex Kubernetes cluster issues\n- Coordinate multi-tool vulnerability remediation\n- Generate security fix recommendations\n\n### A-S Rank Tasks (Human-Guided)\n- Define organization-wide security guardrails\n- Design zero-trust architecture\n- Build policy-as-code governance frameworks\n- Lead incident response\n\n## How JADE Works\n\n1. **Receives Task**: User or JSA agent presents a security task\n2. **Analyzes Context**: JADE uses RAG to retrieve relevant security knowledge\n3. **Reasons Through Problem**: Applies security domain expertise\n4. **Recommends Actions**: Suggests specific fixes with reasoning\n5. **Learns from Outcomes**: Successful fixes become training data\n\n## JADE's Training Pipeline\n\nJADE is fine-tuned from Qwen2.5-Coder-7B using:\n- **Base Model**: Qwen2.5-Coder-7B-Instruct\n- **Method**: LoRA (Low-Rank Adaptation)\n- **Data**: Security-specific examples from real operations\n- **Format**: Alpaca/ChatML instruction format\n\nTraining happens in GP-SAGEMAKER:\n```\nGP-SAGEMAKER/\n├── 1-GP-GLUE/           # Data processing\n├── 3-jade-model-versions/ # Model artifacts\n└── 4-GP-CLARIFY/        # Evaluation\n```\n\n## JADE's Personality\n\nJADE is designed to be:\n- **Direct**: Gets to the point quickly\n- **Technical**: Speaks in security engineering terms\n- **Confident**: Makes clear recommendations\n- **Humble**: Acknowledges when escalation is needed\n- **Educational**: Explains the \"why\" behind security decisions\n\n## Running JADE\n\n```bash\ncd JADE-AI\npython3 jade.py\n```\n\nJADE runs locally using Ollama, requiring no external API calls for inference. This makes it suitable for air-gapped or security-sensitive environments.", "token_count": 504, "char_count": 2007, "source_file": "2026-01-05-jade-ai-complete.md", "source_title": "JADE AI - Complete Overview", "chunk_index": 1, "total_chunks": 2, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.285817", "content_hash": "42519fd1c9f5569e"}
{"chunk_id": "2026-01-05-jsa-agents-complete_0_8350c59b", "content": "# JSA Agents - Complete Overview\n\n## What is JSA?\n\nJSA (JADE Secure Agent) is the autonomous security worker system in GP-Copilot. While JADE is the brain making decisions, JSA agents are the hands doing the work - they execute security scans, apply fixes, and report results 24/7 without human intervention.\n\n## The Iron Legion Analogy\n\nIn the Iron Man analogy:\n- JADE = Tony Stark (the decision maker)\n- JSA agents = Iron Legion (autonomous drones executing missions)\n\nJSA agents are deployed as Kubernetes pods that continuously monitor, scan, and remediate security issues across target projects.\n\n## JSA Agent Variants\n\n### jsa-ci (CI/CD Security Agent)\n**Focus**: Application security in CI/CD pipelines\n\n**Responsibilities**:\n- SAST (Static Application Security Testing)\n- Secrets detection in code\n- Dependency vulnerability scanning\n- Code quality enforcement\n\n**Scanners Used**:\n- Gitleaks (secrets)\n- Bandit (Python SAST)\n- Semgrep (multi-language SAST)\n- ESLint (JavaScript security)\n- Hadolint (Dockerfile linting)\n- Trivy, Grype, Snyk (dependencies)\n\n**Workload**: ~30% of security automation tasks\n\n### jsa-devsecops (DevSecOps Agent)\n**Focus**: Infrastructure and runtime security\n\n**Responsibilities**:\n- Kubernetes security posture\n- Infrastructure as Code scanning\n- Runtime security monitoring\n- Compliance enforcement\n\n**Scanners Used**:\n- Kubescape (K8s security)\n- Polaris (K8s best practices)\n- Kube-bench (CIS benchmarks)\n- Checkov (Terraform/CloudFormation)\n- tfsec (Terraform security)\n- Conftest (OPA policy testing)\n- Prowler (AWS security)\n\n**Workload**: ~70% of security automation tasks", "token_count": 395, "char_count": 1618, "source_file": "2026-01-05-jsa-agents-complete.md", "source_title": "JSA Agents - Complete Overview", "chunk_index": 0, "total_chunks": 3, "created_at": "2026-01-05T23:19:14.289085", "content_hash": "8350c59bbcb84ccc"}
{"chunk_id": "2026-01-05-jsa-agents-complete_1_4f85d1d5", "content": "## How JSA Works\n\n### The 24/7 Autonomous Loop\n\n```\nScanOrchestrator → RankClassifier → Decision Router\n    (14 NPCs)       (JADE-powered)\n\n         ┌────────────────┬─────────────────┬──────────────┐\n         ▼                ▼                 ▼\n   ┌──────────────┐ ┌──────────────┐ ┌─────────────────┐\n   │ E-D Rank     │ │ C Rank       │ │ B-S Rank        │\n   │ AUTO-FIX     │ │ SLACK APPROVE│ │ ESCALATE        │\n   │              │ │              │ │                 │\n   │ FixOrchestrator │ Approve=Fix  │ │ Human Review    │\n   │ (8 Fixer NPCs)  │ Deny=Escalate│ │ + Context       │\n   └──────────────┘ └──────────────┘ └─────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Rank-Based Decision Routing\n\n| Rank | Automation Level | Action | Example |\n|------|------------------|--------|---------|\n| **E** | 95-100% | Auto-fix immediately | Hardcoded secrets, missing resource limits |\n| **D** | 70-90% | Auto-fix with logging | SQL injection, XSS, dependency CVEs |\n| **C** | 40-70% | Slack approval required | Network policies, multi-file IaC changes |\n| **B** | 20-40% | Escalate to human | Architecture changes, compliance gaps |\n| **S** | 0-5% | Escalate immediately | Org-wide policy, incident response |\n\n## NPCs (Non-Player Characters)\n\nJSA uses NPCs as its tools. NPCs are deterministic wrappers around security tools - they don't make decisions, they just run tools and normalize output.\n\n### Scanner NPCs (14 total)\n- **Secrets**: GitleaksNPC\n- **SAST**: BanditNPC, SemgrepNPC, EslintNPC\n- **Dependencies**: TrivyNPC, GrypeNPC, SnykNPC\n- **Kubernetes**: KubescapeNPC, PolarisNPC, KubeBenchNPC\n- **IaC**: CheckovNPC, TfsecNPC, ConftestNPC\n- **Quality**: HadolintNPC\n\n### Fixer NPCs (7 total)\n- SecretsFixerNPC\n- CodeFixerNPC\n- DependencyFixerNPC\n- KubernetesFixerNPC\n- CIFixerNPC\n- ConftestFixerNPC\n- GHAFixerNPC", "token_count": 541, "char_count": 1804, "source_file": "2026-01-05-jsa-agen